Here's a complete example of a C# MCP server wrapping a REST API with stdio transport.

---

### **Program.cs** ÔÇö stdio transport with DI

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only ÔÇö stdout is the JSON-RPC protocol channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient("WeatherApi", client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.weather.example.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();  // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

### **WeatherTools.cs** ÔÇö tool class wrapping a REST API

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(IHttpClientFactory httpFactory, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get the current weather for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetCurrentWeather(
        [Description("City name, e.g. 'Seattle' or 'London'")] string city,
        [Description("Temperature unit: 'celsius' or 'fahrenheit'")] string unit = "celsius",
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching weather for {City}", city);
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("WeatherApi");
        var json = await client.GetStringAsync(
            $"/v1/current?city={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}&unit={unit}",
            cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a 5-day weather forecast for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetForecast(
        [Description("City name")] string city,
        [Description("Number of days (1-5)")] int days = 5,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("WeatherApi");
        var json = await client.GetStringAsync(
            $"/v1/forecast?city={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}&days={days}",
            cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }
}
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | How it works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | DI services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>` are injected via the constructor. The class is resolved from the DI container per-request. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services appear as method parameters and are resolved automatically. |

**Key rule:** The SDK distinguishes tool parameters from DI services automatically. Only parameters with `[Description]` appear in the tool schema. Services like `CancellationToken`, `ILogger<T>`, `HttpClient`, `IMcpServer`, and `IProgress<T>` are **injected silently** ÔÇö the LLM never sees them.

The constructor injection style (shown above) is preferred when tools share a service like `IHttpClientFactory`, since you configure it once in the constructor rather than repeating it on every method.

### Scaffolding commands

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n WeatherMcpServer
cd WeatherMcpServer
dotnet add package ModelContextProtocol
dotnet build && dotnet run
```

The server will start and wait for JSON-RPC messages on stdin. Test it with the [MCP Inspector](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/inspector) or configure it in your IDE's `mcp.json`.
